<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-162-078 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 862 350</DOCID><JOURNAL>CVGIP: Image Understanding  May 1991 v53 n3 p297(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Characterization of right-handed and left-handed shapes.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hel-Or, Yaacov; Peleg, Shmuel; Avnir, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Planar objects are chiral, or handed, in two dimensions if they donot have a symmetry axis in the 2D plane; a right hand will not besimilar to a left hand unless it is viewed through a mirror.andP;  Theset of all human hands can thus be divided into two classes, eachof which has its own specific chirality.andP;  This trait is especiallysignificant in the study of elementary particles whose chiralityis a result of their spin.andP;  Molecules can also be classified intotwo possible configurations: D (dextro) chirality and L (levo)chirality, each of which has distinct chemical characteristics.andP;  Aset of 2D shapes is examined, and their chirality is determined.andO;Those shapes that are found to be chiral are then classifiedaccording to their chirality class.andP;  Chirality is a form ofasymmetry, so it is theoretically sufficient to check whether anobject has reflective symmetry, but almost no real object isexactly symmetric, so it must be determined whether the lack ofsymmetry is a dominant characteristic of the object.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SymmetricalTheoretical ResearchImage ProcessingMeasurementNew TechniqueTwo-Dimensional GraphicsShapeMathematical ModelsEdge Detection.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The shapes on the right are mirror images of the shapes on theleft. (chart)Illustration of the definitions of boundary pixels. (chart)Properties of edge segments in rotation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>